Econometrics - ECON 426

Least squares estimator in the presence of heteroskedasticity

Recall that there are two problems with using the least squares estimator in the presence of heteroskedasticity:

  1. The least squares estimator, although still being unbiased, is no longer best

  2. The usual least squares standard errors are incorrect, which invalidates interval estimates and hypothesis tests

Heteroskedasticity-Consistent Standard Errors

A consistent estimator for this variance has been developed and is known as:

  • White’s heteroskedasticity-consistent standard errors, or Heteroskedasticity robust standard

  • The term “robust” is used because they are valid in large samples for both heteroskedastic and homoskedastic errors

Robust Standard Errors

data("food",package="PoEdata")
mod1 <- lm(food_exp~income, data=food)
summ(mod1,digits=4,robust="HC0")
MODEL INFO:
Observations: 40
Dependent Variable: food_exp
Type: OLS linear regression 

MODEL FIT:
F(1,38) = 23.7888, p = 0.0000
R² = 0.3850
Adj. R² = 0.3688 

Standard errors: Robust, type = HC0
-------------------------------------------------------
                       Est.      S.E.   t val.        p
----------------- --------- --------- -------- --------
(Intercept)         83.4160   27.1094   3.0770   0.0039
income              10.2096    1.7857   5.7173   0.0000
-------------------------------------------------------

Robust Standard Errors

Long J. S., Ervin L. H. (2000). suggest “HC3” and is the default.

summ(mod1,digits=4,robust=T)

or

summ(mod1,digits=4,robust="HC3")
MODEL INFO:
Observations: 40
Dependent Variable: food_exp
Type: OLS linear regression 

MODEL FIT:
F(1,38) = 23.7888, p = 0.0000
R² = 0.3850
Adj. R² = 0.3688 

Standard errors: Robust, type = HC3
-------------------------------------------------------
                       Est.      S.E.   t val.        p
----------------- --------- --------- -------- --------
(Intercept)         83.4160   28.6509   2.9115   0.0060
income              10.2096    1.8862   5.4128   0.0000
-------------------------------------------------------

Long J. S., Ervin L. H. (2000). “Using Heteroscedasticity Consistent Standard Errors in the Linear Regression Model.” The American Statistician, 54, 217–224.
